segments.text: who's Professor of Health and Physical Education and has been at Texas A&M since 1972.
We're going to talk about this department primarily and the impact of changes in at Texas A&M and how it has affected the college, I mean the Department of Health and Physical Education.
So if we can just talk to, well from 1972 that you arrived, what are some of the major things that you have seen happen
And you're talking about the department rather than the college.
Well, both.
Because I mean, the department is an integral part of the college, so we'll probably be talking about both, but it can be either.
I probably can respond better to the department.
OK, that would be great.
All right.
I'll try to do a bunch.
All right.
I think one of the major changes that have had impact on the entire college as well as the department
is the enrollment explosion.
When I came in 1972, we had about 18,000 students, I guess.
And for four or five years after that, we added the equivalent of a small college, a state college, each year.
That's had major impact on us, I think.
Then the other thing that happened was, as that enrollment
grew larger, the proportion of civilian students, so-called civilian students, to Corps of Cadets changed.
The Corps still remained a viable force on this campus.
But when I first came here in 1972, about half of my class would be wearing uniforms, at least.
And now we see one every now and then.
Nobody has mentioned that.
That's interesting.
I think that's made, it's allowed some things to happen.
not necessarily for the better, but different than what they would have evolved had the Corps continued to be the dominant.
Though it still is a very strong force, it's not the dominant force it was in 1972 when I came.
I think you have to identify the changing of the guard at the dean's office as one of the things that happened that made a difference.

Dean Hubert, when he was Dean, I think it was important for us to have gone through that period of time with him because he was a very strong person, had strong ideas, often domineering and autocratic, but nevertheless, once you convinced him that something needed to happen, you could pretty well count on it happening because he pushed it through the university in the same fashion.
Dean Corrigan
came along though with an entirely different orientation and a much broader vision of what education is all about.
I'm not sure I want that.
Well, I'm getting that from everybody.
It's a very, very similar type of perception or observation.
And it is.
It's leadership style.
It's 180 degree difference.
And that's valid.
what I'm hearing is that, you know, we got what we needed at the time, and then this one was right for these times, and so change is inevitable, and that leadership that Hubert had was so necessary.
At the time, I expect that's right, and it was a materialistic, materialistic approach to administration, and we were a military school at that time, almost exclusively.
But even so, Dean Corrigan has opened up an entirely different way of looking at things.
When you went to, as an administrator, when you went to Dean Hubert's office, you made sure that you were well prepared and you rehearsed and you didn't make any mistakes.
Now that was good in that it made you do your homework.
It was bad in that there was no room for experimenting and creativity.
In Dean Corrigan's case, on the other hand, nothing is sacred.
You can say what's on your mind.
He allows you to experiment with ideas and thoughts and things.
Consequently, I think creativity is higher than it's ever been because of that.
Another change that occurred, both at the college and the department level, it was extremely important at the departmental level, but it was because of college change that allowed us to
And that is that we began to look at the College of Education, and this department especially, as being not just teacher preparation as its mission.
That we were preparing educators not just for the public schools.
That made all the difference in the world in our program.
When did that come about, more or less?
It's hard to say.
It was beginning to happen around 1972 when I came.
I think it was a case of the barrier was beginning to erode along then.
Probably it was 74, 75, or somewhere along in there before it really was formalized.
And I can't recall the year, but I know the event.
What we introduced was a curriculum in something we call American Humanics.
The American Humanics was a broad-based program across campus in which
You prepared people for human services like scout masters and executive directors of boy scout and girl scout programs and YMCA programs and things like that, social type programs.
So we began to advertise a program in which you could get a degree in physical education and health education and not necessarily be prepared yourself to teach in public schools.
EDCL, on the other hand, was a little slower in evolving at that point, but they have evolved at that point, especially with their graduate programs.
And what's happened there is that colleges of medicine across the country began to become real concerned about the kind of teachers they were.
The worst teaching in the world for a long time was in colleges of medicine.
It may still be, I don't know, but I think it's a lot better.
And here was a group of people who were really well-versed in pedagogy.
And they began to see themselves as educational directors of colleges of medicine.
And they began to hire those type of people in colleges of medicine.
Several texts were published on medical education along about that time.
And that made a lot of difference to us because roughly half our students, our majors now, are not in teacher preparation.
I think that's important because our field
of physical education has always had more people prepared to teach than there were room for them to teach.
And we didn't need those many folks.
Has the department been growing steadily still?
We've been staying about the same for the past, oh, seven years, I guess, maybe eight years.
Which is about how many?
About 800 majors.
Now that includes, that's undergrad.
So about 70, that's going to depend on when you count.
It's between 700 and 800 at all times.
How about graduates?
I'm going to guess again, but roughly we have about 200 graduate students.
Now, that includes all of our programs.
That's health education, physical education, and then all the specializations, which includes exercise physiology and motor learning.
How have those all been created or come into being?
You know, there's so much diversity in the department now, and I don't think anybody, until they come and see this facility, realize the kinds of things that you're doing.
At least I didn't until we saw it for the Development Council, and that was a real eye-opener.
How do you get that across?
How do people find out that it's here, and then how did it happen?
We suffer from the knowledge curve in that regard.
We still do.
Still there are people who don't know.
When they hear the word physical education, they think basketball and track and roll out the ball type thing.
But it's getting better.
My perception of our reputation on this campus is that it's very, very good and it's getting better.
And I think to a large extent it's because of our association with the faculty senate.
When the faculty senate was created,
That forced us into interaction with faculty from across the campus.

Management or administration, well, administration is not a good term, but a tool for making final decisions for the university was done by the old academic council, which was all department heads and deans and just a few faculty.
So with the coming of the Faculty Senate, that changed that and threw faculties together and gave them opportunities for mutual understanding of one another.
And I think it's been good.
If it doesn't do anything else, I think it's been good for them.
Are you part of the Faculty Senate?
Fortunately or unfortunately, I've been a member of the Senate since its inception.
This is my last year.
When was it started?
Let me see.
I'm in my sixth year.
Let me see if that's right now.
Well, I can check that out.
Maybe the fifth year.
Okay.
Time flies when you have fun.
I believe it's been five years over there.
Okay.
I can count the speakers.
There was McDermott, and then there was Murray Milford, and then there was John Lonnie, and Sam Black, and now Dick Chamoy.
So there's speakers in the Senate.
So this is the fifth year of the Senate.
When would I be able to get some of the...
like, say, minutes or some of the documents of what's gone on in the Senate.
Are they in the archives?
Yes.
Patty Steele is the person in contact.
And she's in the faculty senate office, which is located in the YMCA, the building that's there.
I can file.
Janine, what's a good one for faculty senate office?
Good one.
OK.
I imagine that would have some good.
Oh, she'll have everything.
Background information to hang the College of Education decisions and things on, possibly?
I would think so, at least the most recent decisions.
Okay.
Decisions in the last two or three years, in a way.
Is there one, any particular one that you feel have decisions of the faculty senate that have affected the College of Education the most?
Oh, the core curriculum.
Right.
Of course, made an impact on all of our curriculum.
it affected education less than it did other curricula, like engineering, for example.
Because education has always had a strong liberal arts background.
And so in our curriculum, for example, we only had to change a couple of courses, and we were in total compliance.
However, we took that opportunity to go through a total curriculum revision.
Consequently, we have a curriculum we like a lot better than we've had in the past.
But now, 994 is beginning to come along, and so we're not sure how that's going to affect.
Okay, and the mission of the college and of your department, I'm sure, is still the same as it is for any land grant, which is the teaching, research, and service.
How is that balanced in your department, the focus?
I think in any research institution, you've got to have a strong research thrust.
If you make me put figures on that, I would say that research is equally as important as teaching.
And service, or what I choose to call citizenship, is third in that category.
However, an individual faculty
may have different priorities.
For example, I have faculty that I have designated as being researcher teachers.
They work primarily in the performance laboratory.
And their job is probably more like 40, 30, 40% research, 30% teaching, and then 20% service.
And then I have other faculty who are teacher researchers.
In that case, they're
heavy responsibilities in teaching, but they also have to do a legitimate amount of research.
How many do you have on your faculty?
About.
It depends on when you ask, but about, well, we have 101 faculty and grad assistants.
I just counted those last week.
That's headcount now, not FTE.
And about 25 of those, or more like 35 of those, are graduate assistants.
So what does that make?
About 70, 76 to 80.
Now, a large number of those, 35 of them, would be lecturers who teach in our basic activity program.
So we have actual prof-soil-ranked faculty are about 28 to 29.
OK.
Is there a lot of collaboration among your faculty with other departments or even with other colleges?
Quite a bit.
A lot of collaboration within the department, because you've got motor learning, for example.
It's very difficult for them to do any research without collaborating with exercise physiology and also with biomechanics.
Those people also collaborate heavily

people in vet school, quite a bit going on with engineering right now, particularly between motor learning and engineering, because a lot of the things we're doing in motor learning relates directly to engineering.
What degree are, in other words, how are the students
Can students that are in engineering be taking these classes, or is that a collaboration?
Normally it's through research.
It's research collaboration.
However, we do have some engineering students who take some of our courses, and of course we take some of theirs.
We take a lot of the veterinary medicine courses, the exercise physiology people do, because a lot of the same information that we need is provided there.
In fact, they'll take 14 to 16 hours over there, their doctoral students will.
When did the doctoral program come into being?
Do you know more?
I mean, I've seen it, I just don't.
Were you, was it already in place when you were here?
It was in place when I came.
It was around, and I'm going to have to guess, but it was around 68.
But Linus Dowell, to tell you almost precisely if you know him, he's on my faculty.
Brian Cope, I can get the same information for you.
Now, our health education doctoral program
didn't come into existence until about 75.
And that's a guess, too, but it'll be within two years.
How about the view, and you mentioned that a little bit in passing, about how people don't know about or are not aware of some of the things that go on.
I was looking at what are the perceptions of outsiders of the College of Education.
And again, sometimes I even have trouble
thinking of you all as the College of Education because you're over here and you don't make the connection all the time.
What about people's perceptions outside the college?
Outside the College of Education or even beyond that, outside in the external environment?
Do you know or have a feel for how do people perceive this area or this department or its contribution?
I think it's a common mistake often made that
People don't perceive us as being part of education.
There's a lot of common mistakes made.
One is they perceive us as being all activity, and that's all we do.
Of course, that is a major portion of what we do.
I don't want to belittle that.
We still think that's pretty important.
Then there's a misconception that, for example, the folks in engineering, we're working with our people in our human performance laboratory,
and didn't even equate human performance laboratory to the department.
And so, you know, you have that kind of thing going on.

With a diversified program, you've got individual chairs who are leading those programs who have full freedom because, you know, I encourage them to take that full freedom to engage conversation with their components across campus.
And here's two subcomponents that talk to one another and not know who the parent of that particular group is.
A large university is really an unstructured thing.
When you get right down to it, it's really a lot of unstructured stuff.
Now, a lot of programs like mine are not in colleges of education, too.
Okay, that might be the problem.
And that may be what you were getting at.
Okay, maybe so.
A lot of schools, and I could name you four or five, have our colleges into themselves.
The University of Maryland is a good example of the College of Health and Physical Education.
In fact, I think they changed their name recently, but it's still basically the same thing.
Indiana has that.
The University of Florida has that.
Do you think that would ever happen here?
I don't.
I don't foresee it right immediately.
What we would like to see happen is for us to be recognized as a school within the College of Education.
I've approached Dean Cargan about this
What that would get for us though is as large as we are and as much responsibility as division chairs have, they don't get much recognition for that in terms of reallocated time.
They're doing all that off the corner of the desk.
They teach a full teaching load and then they're managing a subunit off the side of the desk.
If we were identified as a school, we could have titles, you know, university-recognized titles in which they could get some reality of time.
So there'd be some advantage to that.
Well, you say they're working on these off-site, like, give me an example.
Well, Robert Hurley, for example, is a full professor of health education, and he teaches a full teaching load.
When I say full, it's not quite a full load, but I'm not able to give him as much release time to manage the health education division as I'd like to.
So he's, as far as the university is concerned, he's like any other faculty member on campus.
But he's got about eight or nine or ten faculty and a student enrollment of about 300 that he manages.
And I can't formally recognize him for that.
And should he leave, I can't promote someone into his spot and have a salary increment based on
on the administrative department because the administrative department doesn't exist as far as the university is concerned.
And if it was a school, that would be all different.
That would help solve it.
What's the dean's reaction?
Does he feel that he's...
He's not enamored with it.
And I don't really know why he's...
He may see that as a first step toward breaking off and becoming a separate college.
I personally don't view it that way.
It may be that...
that he has information from the Provost's office that I don't have in terms of the legitimacy of that.
However, I do know that the College of Business has one program under it that is a school of accounting or something like that.
I'm not sure what it is.
Interesting.
To say that we would never become a college, you just don't know.
But that's not one of the things that we're in.
striving for at this point.
We're very happy with the administrative rank that we have.
Well, that leads me into the next one about the vision for the future and what you think the College of Education will be like possibly in, I would say, year 2000 and beyond maybe.
Where do you think we're going?
I think we're going in one of two ways and we sure better get a handle on it.
We've become so specialized
And not just, now we have over here, but EDCI even has become specialized.
We've become so specialized until we're learning more and more.
Who was it, George Bernard Shaw, that said we learn more and more about less and less until we know almost everything about nothing.
I'm afraid that if we aren't careful, we're headed exactly in that direction.
It's gotten to the point where we're so specialized until one specialization won't talk to the other specialization
or won't listen to another because they don't feel they know what they're talking about.
I worry about that.
I worry about it in my fields more than I do about the college because it's my business to worry about it right now.

But our exercise physiology people, for example, are becoming so specialized in exercise physiology until they don't see their role as the researchers which are supposed to provide information for the people who are teaching the activity program to them.
They see themselves as researchers
Heaven knows what.
What are we going to do with all that information?
Publishing, maybe?
Is there a lot of pressure still in your department or within the college for publishing and all that?
Do you feel it?
Because some people say it's just within and they put it on themselves.
No.
I do believe that the faculty create most of the pressure.
not for themselves, but for one another.
I think the administrators have a lot less, are placing a lot less pressure on faculty groups to publish than are the faculty groups themselves.
Let me give you that example.
If I have Professor A, who has a good teaching record, a decent publication record, I feel very strongly that

If I could take Professor A to Dean Cargan, I can make the case that Dean Cargan would approve him, send him to the provost, the provost would approve him, and they'd move out on to the tenure structure.

But you run that same professor through a faculty group, and the faculty group starts counting publications and starts applying all kinds of criteria to that particular person that are perceived more than real, I think.
And consequently, my feeling is that other faculty are tougher on faculty than the administration is.
And do you have to go through that process of other faculty before you can go on?
Yes, yes.
Through your department.
That's right.
However, I can make a recommendation that's contrary to the committee's recommendation.
For example, the committee might not approve them and I could send them forward approved, but I also have to send forward the committee's recommendation at the same time.
Or the committee may approve, and I could deny.
But again, I have to send forward the committee.
Does each department have complete autonomy on how they handle that tenure?
Or are you pretty much structured?
Well, you don't have complete autonomy, but you have a lot of freedom.
You do have to have criteria spelled out, and it has to be approved by the dean, and this is where you're going to operate.
And we look amazingly alike.
to someone else we may look amazingly different but I think given that we look amazing.
Now you started to say that we're going either one of two ways and one of them was the specialization and one was the other.
Yeah.
The other approach is for us to recognize that we're becoming so specialized so much so until we are losing sight of what's really important and finally
redirect ourselves to some type of organization that makes sense, where there's good communication between across disciplines and specializations, and we only decide what we're all about.
What would bring that about the best?
Do you have any ideas?
Gosh, if I knew that, Sylvia, I'd be doing it right now.
And that's tough.
Yes, it is.
And I'm hearing that from a lot of people.
What I'm trying to do in my department is make sure that we talk to one another, keep the groups meeting together and talking together.
And I'm looking for some ways that we can collaborate our research from the exercise physiologist to the practitioner.
I think the same thing could happen in other fields in the college.
But let me give you an example.
Charlie Shea is our motor learning instructor.
And he's doing some things in the laboratory that are very technical and very high level.

But one thing he's learned, it's almost like a spin-off, is that if you take, and this is going to sound very simple, but it makes an important thing, if you take a mallet and try to drive a peg, okay, that you have to learn how much, and you've got an electronic device set up so that your force is between two
If you hit it too hard, you've erred.
If you haven't hit it hard enough, you've erred.
He's learned that if you have the same repeated measures in the same spot, you can soon learn to do that.
But then when you change the parameter, you can't do it.
And so what he's been able to demonstrate in the laboratory is that the best way to practice that skill is to hit it from one
under one set of parameters, and then hit it for another set, and then another set, and then another set.
In other words, vary the parameters constantly.
Now, that has all kinds of ramifications for teaching physical education activities.
And the most obvious one is in putting a golf ball, for example.
Most people who play golf, to practice putting, they get a set distance, put four or five balls down, and put the same stroke, same distance.
His research says that's not a very productive way of learning the skill.
You'd be better off putting it from one distance, then another distance, and then a third distance, and so forth.
Well, now, why not take what he's found in the laboratory?
Now, he's demonstrated it in the laboratory, but it hasn't been demonstrated in the field.
But we have some people teaching activity courses in the field who could very easily conduct that research under his guidance.
He sets up the parameters.
They'd be the technician, collect the data.
The two of them together write it in.
And then you're building a camaraderie between the two that
Well, and also the fact that you have this laboratory and that you make it available to people and people come in and get this test, or at least I think you do, I know you did.
Sure, yeah.
Isn't that an excellent way of...
I think so.
And are people taking advantage of that to any extent?
They are.
To a large extent, not to the extent that we allow for them to, but to a large extent.
I think the thing that Dean Cargill tried to set up with the independent school districts last year
is a step in that direction.
You know, health, wellness weekend type things?

Well, no, I was referring to a meeting we had in the Woodlands, I believe, in which we brought in researchers from the public schools to interface with researchers from higher education on the idea of making theirs available.
Yeah, it's still in progress, isn't it?
I understand there was, I think, Chris Foreman was in San Antonio for a meeting on that last week.
Good.
I think that's a step toward building that camaraderie, keeping you focused on what you're all about rather than getting information just for information's sake.

Can we talk just for a few minutes about highlights and things that you feel, and there's a little reluctance in people talking about their own contribution, but what are some of the things that you feel have been most meaningful since you have been here?
And does anything stand out in particular?
I know there's been lots of things over such a long time.
I think there's, this is difficult, but there's two or three things that have happened.
Now, whether I had anything to do with them, I was around when it happened.
One is we
were able to get much improved facilities over what we had.
A lot of people contributed to that.
And I happened to be the one that came along at the right time to organize the move and finalize the building.
But Dr. Landis, who was probably ahead of me, had worked a long time to get us in that position.
But I think that made a lot of difference in our program is better facilities.

I think another thing that has happened that I was involved in was the, this is going to sound contradictory, considering what I just said, but the splitting away of health education and physical education.
And that happened in this department in the 70s, 74, 75.
And I think I had something to do with that, along with Dr. Hurley, who was on our staff.
Until that time, the program was a health and physical education curriculum.
In other words, someone going through that curriculum was certified to teach not just physical education, but also health education.
But what was happening was you were prepared to teach physical education, and you had six hours of health, for example, which didn't prepare you to teach health at all.
And by splitting that apart, I think we now have strong discipline in physical education and strong discipline in health education.
Is health education still a requirement in the public school?
Yes.
And physical ed, I know.
That's right.
At the secondary level of health, we've lost some of the requirements at the junior high level.
And at the elementary level, it's in the hands of the self-contained classroom teacher.
Do you have any follow-up system for your students and how many go into actual teaching and how many stay?
I'm hearing a lot about the retention and how a lot of people are not staying in the profession and we're spending a lot of money to educate.
Do you have a feel for that?
I don't have a feel for it, but I've got the system in place to get the feel.
We're in the process right now.
About four years ago, we established a feedback procedure in which we administer questionnaires to our graduates and then
A year later, we follow up with them.
Two years later, we follow up with them.
And then five years later, we follow up with them.
And that data is coming in, and it has not been analyzed.
But we should be able to have some data.
